AG-7 RETRIEVAL_SOURCES
Query generator:
After AG-3 resolves one real ProgramIdentity, pass program_name, brand, domain,
and country_or_region to query_generator.py. Use Gemini 2.5 Flash to generate at
most 15 structured Tavily queries. Prioritize difficult and high-value schema
fields: point value, partnerships, sentiment, competitors, personalization,
gamification, membership count, earn rate, qualification criteria, and app
ratings. Queries are search strings only; never output factual claims from this
node.
The validated domain from AG-3 is authoritative. If Gemini outputs
detected_category as Other or a conflicting category, the Python parser must
preserve the input validator's domain. Query generator output must include
detected_category, resolved_corporate_parent, geography, priority_fields,
query_strategy_summary, estimated_web_coverage, field_query_map, and structured
queries with query_id, query, intent, target_fields, and source_type.
Gemini query IDs like Q01 are external_query_id values. The Python parser must
create internal SearchQuery.query_id values for graph joins, translate
field_query_map references to those internal IDs, and preserve the Gemini ID as
external_query_id for audit/debugging.

Use multiple source classes:
official program pages, terms and conditions, FAQs, partner pages, app store
listings, app reviews, recent news, press releases, Reddit/FlyerTalk/community
forums, complaint sources, and relevant review pages.

Tavily retrieval node:
Send each generated SearchQuery to Tavily with max_results=5. Store only
URL-routing metadata: url, canonical_url, title, Tavily score, originating
query, query_id, and source_type. Do not store Tavily snippets as evidence
content because Firecrawl is the scraping/content source. Merge all query
results into one deduplicated set by canonical_url before passing data to the
next fetch/sanitization node. If the same canonical URL appears multiple times,
keep the highest Tavily score.

Firecrawl scraper node:
Pass the deduplicated RetrievedUrl set into firecrawl_scraper.py. Firecrawl must
scrape every URL as the actual content source. PDF parsing is enabled so PDF
URLs such as annual reports can also be scraped when present; this node is not
PDF-only. Return one JSON block per URL with keys url and content, where content
is the raw scraped markdown/text blob. Do not force schema extraction inside
Firecrawl; schema mapping belongs to the later chunking/extraction node. Failed
URLs should still produce a block with content null and an error for
auditability.

Post-Firecrawl ingestion node:
Immediately after Firecrawl, run a domain-agnostic ingestion pipeline:
Raw Document Store -> Semantic Chunking -> Gemini Structured Extraction ->
Packet Normalization -> Identity Hashing. This stage outputs
state["normalized_packets"]. It must not perform conflict detection,
adjudication, debate, reconciliation, canonicalization, brief generation, or
report generation.

Raw Document Store:
Persist Firecrawl markdown/text blobs in SQLite as RawDocument records. Skip
pages under 100 words. Generate url_hash as sha256(url)[:16]. Store url,
url_hash, content, word_count, query_id, entity_name, domain, retrieved_at,
source_authority, and source metadata. Writes must be idempotent.

Semantic Chunking:
Split markdown on headings, ignore sections under 30 words, and split sections
over about 1500 words at paragraph boundaries. Return chunk_id, chunk_text,
source_url, and target_fields. The chunker must contain no loyalty-specific
logic, aliases, or hardcoded brands.

Gemini Structured Extraction:
Extraction is runtime-schema driven via FieldDef, ObjectTypeDef, and
SchemaConfig. The extractor itself must know nothing about loyalty programs or
any future domain. Gemini must extract only explicitly stated facts from the
chunk text, never infer, never fill gaps, and never use training knowledge.
When no caller-supplied SchemaConfig exists, Kobie should provide its
project-level default runtime schema containing every AG-4 field path. This is
configuration, not extractor logic; the extractor must still enforce whatever
runtime schema it receives.
Each field must be one of EXTRACTED, NOT_FOUND, or AMBIGUOUS. EXTRACTED values
must include a source_snippet. Missing evidence remains value null with status
NOT_FOUND. Unclear evidence remains value null with status AMBIGUOUS. On JSON
parse failure retry once, then return an empty list without crashing.

Normalization and identity hashing:
Normalize extracted values by lowercasing strings, stripping whitespace,
deduplicating and sorting arrays, and converting numeric strings to numeric
types. Preserve source_snippet unchanged. Never alter NOT_FOUND or AMBIGUOUS
values. Add normalized_at. Generate identity_hash from object_type, extracted
identity fields, and scope.geography using sha256(... )[:24]. Only fields with
status EXTRACTED participate. If no identity fields are extracted, generate a
UUID hash and log a warning. Persist normalized packets to SQLite.

Zero-result gate:
If fewer than 2 usable pages have more than 150 tokens, stop before extraction.

AG-8 CONFIDENCE_SCORING
High volatility fields:
earn_rate_base, earn_rate_unit, tier_thresholds, redemption_value, cpp,
partner availability, app ratings, recent changes.
Weights: recency 0.50, authority 0.25, corroboration 0.25.

Low volatility fields:
program_name, brand, domain, industry, tier names.
Weights: recency 0.20, authority 0.50, corroboration 0.30.

Conflict policy:
If score gap > 0.20, auto-resolve to the stronger claim.
If score gap < 0.20, trigger Debate Node 1 or return manual_review_needed.

AG-9 DATABASE_TABLES
runs, program_identities, sources, pages, chunks, claims, conflicts, briefs,
conversations.

SQLite rules:
Use WAL mode, busy_timeout, per-thread connections, string IDs, and ISO-8601
datetime strings. Store JSON as text. Hydrate rows through Pydantic models.

AG-10 MODULE_BUILD_ORDER
1. schemas.py
2. db.py
3. providers.py
4. validation.py
5. query_generator.py
6. retrieval.py
7. extraction.py
8. verification.py
9. narration.py
10. comparison.py
11. converse.py
12. graph.py
13. app.py

AG-11 ACCEPTANCE_TESTS
Input validation:
known aliases resolve correctly; ambiguous names ask clarification; unknown
names stop before API calls.

Extraction:
every claim has field_path, value_json, status, source_url when supported,
access_date when supported, confidence, and volatility.

Verification:
unsupported claims cannot reach narrator/comparator/converse.

Narration:
brief is 500-1000 words; each factual sentence maps to claim IDs.

Comparison:
factual_mismatch, missing_in_a, missing_in_b, manual_review_needed, and null are
separate outcomes.
Compare UI:
accepts Input A and Input B in side-by-side cards. It must not introduce a new
research pipeline; it triggers the same single-program pipeline twice in
parallel. Each card must include the
same input verifier clarification loop used by single mode, including follow-up
questions when confidence is below 0.90. Once resolved, each input must execute
the same validation, retrieval, extraction, verification, and narration workflow
used for a single program before any comparison display is generated.

Converse:
available after final output generation. It answers only from stored claim/brief
JSON; absent data returns not_found/manual_review_needed.
"""


